rs.md\n36\t\n37\t## Key Rules\n38\t\n39\t0. Framework / infrastructure / specification / skill / verificator / aggregator / materializer\n40\t   changes in `arf/`, generic `meta/`, and generic boilerplate are not task work. Do not create a\n41\t   `tasks/tXXXX_*` folder for such changes.\n42\t1. All CLI tool calls MUST be wrapped in `arf/scripts/utils/run_with_logs.py`\n43\t2. One task = one folder = one branch = one PR\n44\t3. **NEVER** modify files outside the task folder. Only top-level tooling files may change:\n45\t   `pyproject.toml`, `uv.lock`, `ruff.toml`, `.gitignore`\n46\t4. Each task stage and each action is a separate well-described commit\n47\t5. Nothing in a completed task folder may be changed; use the corrections mechanism in later tasks\n48\t6. Run `uv run flowmark --inplace --nobackup <changed.md>` on edited markdown files, then run\n49\t   `uv run ruff check --fix . && uv run ruff format . && uv run mypy .` before commit\n50\t7. Framework tests live in `arf/tests/`. Task-specific tests live in\n51\t   `tasks/$TASK_ID/code/test_*.py`. Do not create or use a top-level `tests/` directory.\n52\t8. Full data normalization; no duplication across task folders\n53\t9. **Always use aggregators to enumerate cross-task data.** Never walk `tasks/` with\n54\t   Glob/Grep/find/Explore to list tasks, papers, suggestions, answers, datasets, libraries, models,\n55\t   predictions, costs, metrics, or metric results. Aggregators in `arf/scripts/aggregators/` apply\n56\t   the corrections overlay; raw filesystem walks silently miss corrections and produce stale\n57\t   answers. See `arf/docs/reference/aggregators.md` for the full list and flags.\n58\t\n59\t## Task Workflow\n60\t\n61\t* Tasks live in `tasks/tXXXX_slug/` (t prefix + 4-digit ID + underscore slug)\n62\t* Each task runs in its own git worktree on branch `task/<task_id>`\n63\t* Multiple tasks can execute in parallel (each in a separate worktree)\n64\t* New tasks branch: `new_tasks/<first_index>-<last_index>`\n65\t* Mandatory stages: research -> planning -> implementation -> analysis -> reporting\n66\t* Every step must be logged in `logs/`; verificators enforce this\n67\t* Aggregators collect data across tasks AND apply corrections overlays — use them instead of walking\n68\t  `tasks/` directly (see rule 9)\n69\t* Format specs for task documents: `arf/specifications/`\n70\t\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"uuid":"f0a5578d-7299-4625-ac25-bbb46c4191bd","timestamp":"2026-05-02T20:51:47.265Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"9287bc98-7199-4281-bd21-96c2e58bf7fa","userType":"external","entrypoint":"sdk-cli","cwd":"/Users/lysaniuk/Documents/reasoning-scale2-worktrees/t0027_phase2_5_abc_rerun_with_fixed_b_and_c","sessionId":"5e2b9b34-3bed-4e0d-96ea-e0949b1b438b","version":"2.1.118","gitBranch":"task/t0027_phase2_5_abc_rerun_with_fixed_b_and_c"}
